Mapping Problem

David Kane

3/25/2019

The purpose of this document is to highlight a mapping problem that is making me crazy. With luck, you can help! I am using data from the Stanford Open Policing Project. Toward the middle of this page is the data for Hartford. (Those new to mapping might want to start with Chapter 7 of Healy. But note that Healy does not use geom_sf the sf stands for simple features and is the current state of the art for making maps in R. To learn about sf, try this three part tutorial.)

It is straightforward to make a map of Hartford:

Note that Hartford is a relatively small city, with 0.1 of width/length in terms of longitude and lattitude. Fortunately, our data seems much more precise than that.

##               district                    location      lat       lng
## 1             WEST END Sisson Ave @ Farmington Ave 41.76668 -72.70736
## 2  SHELDON-CHARTER OAK wyllys st at charter oak pl 41.75642 -72.67362

## 9        NORTH MEADOWS      Jennings Rd @ 91 South 41.78610 -72.65393
## 10            DOWNTOWN               185 ASYLUM ST 41.76680 -72.67620

I just want to plot those 10 points on my map. I have a map and we have some points with appropriate latitude and longitude. The trick is that you want the points to be a special kind of object. Once it is, you can just use it with geom_sf. The answer was in that three part tutorial. Just needed to read it!

sites <- st_as_sf(points, coords = c("lng", "lat"), crs = 4326)

ggplot(data = shapes) +
  geom_sf() +
  geom_sf(data = sites)
